Cloud Run, Cloud SQL, IAM Troubleshooting
Topic
Cloud Run → Cloud SQL Private IP Architecture, IAM Permissions, Service Networking, and Troubleshooting
Objective
Understand how Cloud Run connects to Cloud SQL using a VPC connector and runtime service identity.
Build Cloud SQL private IP networking, enable service networking, and deploy Cloud Run tied to Cloud SQL.
Practice real-world IAM troubleshooting and clean up resources safely.
________________________________________
Key Concepts
Cloud Run
•	Cloud Run has two identities: 
o	Invoker identity → controls who can call the service.
o	Runtime service account (SA) → controls what the service can access.
•	To access Cloud SQL, Cloud Run uses the runtime SA, not the invoker or user.
•	Deploying Cloud Run with a custom SA requires roles/iam.serviceAccountUser on that SA.
Cloud SQL Private IP
•	A Cloud SQL private IP requires: 
o	servicenetworking.googleapis.com enabled.
o	A reserved /24 address block.
o	A VPC peering connection with Google-managed services.
•	Cloud SQL private IP appears in the VPC internal range, not the public IP range.
•	Cloud Run → Cloud SQL private access requires: 
o	A Serverless VPC Connector.
o	The runtime SA to have roles/cloudsql.client.
Serverless VPC Access
•	Connects Cloud Run to internal resources inside your VPC.
•	Must be created with a /28 CIDR.
•	Without this connector, Cloud Run cannot see private IPs or Cloud SQL.
IAM
•	IAM Conditions evaluate at request time, not deployment time.
•	Removing conditional IAM bindings requires all three fields: 
o	title
o	description
o	expression
•	Cloud Run IAM errors (setIamPolicy denied) occur when the user lacks: 
o	roles/run.admin
o	OR roles/editor
o	OR roles/owner
Cleanup
•	Cloud SQL is the only resource with daily cost.
•	Cloud Run, VPC connectors, peered ranges, SQL, and Storage buckets must be deleted individually for full cleanup.
